**How to Rig**

## **Requirements:**

To properly rig your model, you need:

* Roblox Studio  
* The model to rig  
* The script (RigScript.lua) used for rigging, found in the folder containing this document or ExampleRig.rbxl file

## **Step 1: Setup**

**IMPORTANT NOTE: Make a backup of your model before attempting this, in case something goes wrong**

To set up the model for rigging, the model must have these:

* HumanoidRootPart  
* Grouped Limbs  
  * Torso (required, must be directly connected to HumanoidRootPart)  
  * Head (required, must be directly connected to Torso)  
* Pivots  
* All parts must be:  
  * Anchored \= true  
  * Massless \= true  
    * Except for HumanoidRootPart, where Massless \= false  
  * CanTouch \= false  
    * Except for HumanoidRootPart, where CanTouch \= true

3. This is the first layer of objects within Joe’s model:  
   1. Should only contain two objects:

4. Within the Model, each limb should be grouped and labeled separately  
   1. Each limb should also have a part named Pivot

5. Make sure every part is Anchored \= true, CanTouch \= false, Massless \= true  
   1. HumanoidRootPart: Anchored \= true, CanTouch \= true, Massless \= false

## **Step 2: “Skeleton” Values**

The script attached will generate a group of objects that you will need to arrange to set up the “skeleton” of the rig. 

1. Copy and paste ALL lines of the script into Studio’s command bar, then press Enter/Return on your keyboard to run it  
   1. Nothing should happen yet after running it

![][image10] \-\> ![][image11]

2. Select the model you want to rig in the workspace  
   ![][image12]

3. With the model still selected, clear the command bar and type in “Step1()” and then run it  
   1. This should create an ObjectValue with the same name as your model  
      

	![][image13]

Outputs:   
![][image14]

4. Open the ObjectValue in the Explorer tab, it should contain sub-values labeled after the limbs of the model  
   1. Re-arrange these values so that they resemble the hierarchy of the limbs of the model  
      1. HumanoidRootPart MUST be at the root; Torso must belong under HumanoidRootPart, and Head must belong under Torso

   ![][image15]   \-\>  ![][image16]

   

## **Step 3: Rigging**

1. Select the ObjectValue again and clear the command bar, typing in “Step2()” this time and running it  
   ![][image17]      		![][image18]  
     
2. Your model should now be fully rigged, with Motor6Ds in the appropriate joint parts  
   ![][image19]  
     
3. Add an AnimationController OR a Humanoid into the model  
   1. This will allow you to animate the model

![][image20]

4. Congratulations\! You can now animate the model

![][image21]

## **Step 4: Animation Rules**

1. All characters should have at least these animations:  
   1. Idle  
   2. Walk/Run  
   3. Jump  
   4. Fall

2. Frames and loops \- For best results, these animations should have a set amount of frames and/or be looped  
   1. Idle \- Looped  
      1. (Optional) Random Idle Pose \- Not looped  
         1. (Optional, can lead into this with above) Random Idle Pose Loop \- Looped  
   2. Walk/Run \- Looped  
   3. Jump \- Not looped, \~10 frames  
   4. Fall \- Looped  
   5. Attack \- Not looped  
   6. Land \- Not looped

3. Remember to set the Animation Priority for each animation, each one should have the corresponding priority:  
   1. Idle \- Core  
      1. (Optional) Random Idle Pose (Both Start and Loop) \- Core  
   2. Walk/Run \- Idle  
   3. Jump \- Action  
   4. Fall \- Movement  
   5. Attack \- Action  
   6. Land \- Idle

![][image22]

## **Step 5: Model Finalizations**

1. Make sure all parts are (If followed steps above correctly, only need to look at \[d.\]):  
   1. Anchored \= false, except HumanoidRootPart  
   2. Massless \= true, except HumanoidRootPart  
   3. CanCollide \= false, except for HumanoidRootPart  
   4. CanTouch \= false, **including** HumanoidRootPart  
2. Set the base model’s PrimaryPart to HumanoidRootPart

![][image23]

3. Set the following to the HumanoidRootPart  
   1. CustomPhysicalProperties \= true  
   2. Density \= 10  
   3. Elasticity \= 0  
      ![][image24]  
4. Set the model’s Head Transparency \= 0, and add a mesh into it with Scale \= 0,0,0  
   1. This is to allow the player’s name to be displayed without the head having to be visible  
5. (OPTIONAL) Add a new part to the model, called “Hitbox”  
   1. This determines where the character gets hit by attacks  
   2. Set the following to the new part  
      1. Name \= “Hitbox”  
      2. Size \- the size of the hitbox you prefer  
      3. Anchored \= false  
      4. CanCollide \= false  
      5. CanTouch \= true  
      6. Massless \= true  
      7. Transparency \= 1  
   3. Multiple hitboxes are allowed, as long as they follow the rules above  
      1. Be cautious though as the more hitboxes, the more likely for lag to occur

![][image25]

4. Position the hitbox anywhere you prefer for the character, place it in the base model, and attach it by using a WeldConstraint:  
   ![][image26]
